WEBVTT

00:03.522 --> 00:10.209
Each year, Gospel and Life offers a daily devotional during the season of Lent, the 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday.

00:10.670 --> 00:15.335
You can sign up to receive these daily devotionals by email at gospelandlife.com.

00:15.555 --> 00:17.658
That's gospelandlife.com.

00:18.178 --> 00:20.941
Now here's Dr. Keller with today's teaching.

00:28.269 --> 00:32.594
We're just doing a consecutive exposition of the Gospel according to Peter.

00:32.866 --> 00:39.513
First Peter, and I'm going to read to you the same passage we read last week, and just open up what it says.

00:39.573 --> 00:44.819
It's First Peter, it's printed in your bulletin, chapter 1.

00:44.839 --> 00:50.305
And we're going to look at verses 10 to 12, 10, 11, and 12, three verses.

00:52.167 --> 00:52.708
Let's read it.

00:54.030 --> 01:01.618
Concerning this salvation, the prophets who spoke of the grace that was to come to you, searched intently with the greatest care.

01:01.794 --> 01:10.626
trying to find out the time and the circumstances to which the Spirit of Christ in them was pointing when he predicted the sufferings of Christ and the glories that would follow.

01:11.227 --> 01:25.967
It was revealed to them that they were not serving themselves but serving you when they spoke of the things that have now been told to you by those who have preached the gospel to you by the Holy Spirit sent from heaven.

01:26.568 --> 01:31.314
Even angels long to look into these things.

01:31.714 --> 01:35.038
into which things, even angels, long to look.

01:35.959 --> 01:36.799
This is God's word.

01:38.241 --> 01:56.260
Now, actually, we started looking at this last week, and this week we're going to conclude our look at these three little verses, which I'm pretty certain are a kind of a tangent, an addendum, as we said last week, good pastors and good communicators anticipate people's questions.

01:56.801 --> 02:01.426
And the first few verses of Peter, which we looked at in the last couple of weeks, say,

02:01.602 --> 02:27.058
in the first few verses of Peter, Peter says, that if you're a Christian, if you have received salvation, which means deliverance, if you have received this deliverance from your sin, from your brokenness, if you've received this salvation, then when you go into times of trouble, suffering

02:27.586 --> 02:33.658
Instead of that suffering breaking you, it will refine you just like putting metal through a furnace just refines and purifies it.

02:33.738 --> 02:41.454
So if you have this great salvation, Peter says, you will find as you move on through the sufferings, it will just make you better.

02:42.396 --> 02:49.330
We talked about this in the morning services as when I was preparing people for worship.

02:49.442 --> 02:52.885
It's intriguing if you can see this so many ways, so many places in the Bible.

02:53.386 --> 03:03.355
In the book of Mark, chapter 1, we see Jesus Christ has an experience at his baptism of the Holy Spirit, comes down from up above.

03:04.016 --> 03:09.441
And as he receives the Holy Spirit, he gets this assurance that he belongs to the Father.

03:09.782 --> 03:17.249
He hears the voice of the Father saying, this is my Son, whom I love, in whom I am well pleased.

03:17.849 --> 03:18.450
Something

03:18.722 --> 03:19.503
people forget.

03:19.643 --> 03:20.665
Some people miss.

03:20.765 --> 03:21.767
It's so clear right there.

03:22.488 --> 03:28.176
The fullness of the Spirit is always linked to an assurance of your adoption.

03:29.798 --> 03:32.102
The fullness of the Spirit isn't a kind of naked power.

03:32.122 --> 03:33.384
It's not kind of electricity.

03:33.424 --> 03:34.766
Here it comes.

03:35.126 --> 03:36.869
And now I'm able to do more things.

03:37.310 --> 03:48.466
No, it's the power that comes from the realization and the assurance that the great King of heaven is my Father who loves me and is completely pleased with me.

03:49.538 --> 03:53.382
because Jesus Christ is my righteousness and my goodness and my record.

03:53.862 --> 03:55.243
He's my advocate.

03:55.624 --> 03:56.805
He's my priest.

03:59.227 --> 04:03.151
In other words, the power is not an artificial power.

04:03.171 --> 04:04.332
It's not a mechanical power.

04:04.692 --> 04:12.540
It's a personal power that comes just from the excitement and the thrill and the freedom from knowing God's your father.

04:12.560 --> 04:19.506
Now, the minute he experiences that, and by the way, that's just a small tangent, but never forget that,

04:19.682 --> 04:21.184
What does it mean to be filled with the Holy Spirit?

04:21.464 --> 04:27.711
It means to know your Father loves you, to act out of that, to be able to cut that Father love like a knife.

04:27.911 --> 04:29.593
It lays so thick on your Spirit.

04:30.994 --> 04:33.237
That's what it means to be filled with a Spirit.

04:33.257 --> 04:34.238
It's the same thing.

04:34.258 --> 04:39.183
Now, when Jesus experiences that, what are we told?

04:39.224 --> 04:43.108
He's driven out into the wilderness by the Spirit, and he's with the wild beasts.

04:43.688 --> 04:48.754
But as soon as he goes through that terrible experience of temptation in the wilderness, he is prepared

04:48.866 --> 04:50.107
for preaching.

04:50.548 --> 04:52.270
He then begins to preach in a powerful way.

04:52.290 --> 05:07.487
Look, look, an experience of your salvation, an experience of being adopted, an experience of God's love, plus an experience of trouble in the wilderness and wild beasts equals power to serve other people.

05:09.850 --> 05:10.971
Same thing as Peter's saying.

05:11.592 --> 05:16.978
If you understand, you receive your salvation and going into the furnace actually doesn't

05:17.090 --> 05:19.033
turn you into a cinder, it turns you into pure gold.

05:19.073 --> 05:19.534
Same thing.

05:19.915 --> 05:21.337
Now, we get to verse 10.

05:23.020 --> 05:25.223
And suddenly, Peter does a little bit of a digression.

05:25.243 --> 05:26.666
And I think this is the reason why.

05:26.706 --> 05:32.636
Because I think he anticipates somebody saying, OK, I'm a Christian.

05:33.277 --> 05:37.063
I think, at least I believe in all this salvation.

05:37.103 --> 05:38.185
And I believe in Jesus.

05:38.225 --> 05:39.246
And he died for me and all that.

05:39.767 --> 05:41.490
But I'm not rejoicing in my trials.

05:42.722 --> 05:47.910
I'm not moving on through my suffering, feeling like I'm being purified, like pure gold, not at all.

05:47.930 --> 05:49.152
I'm not rejoicing in my sufferings.

05:49.172 --> 05:50.454
What's wrong with me?"

05:50.474 --> 05:54.361
So what Peter actually does is he says, well, concerning the salvation.

05:54.401 --> 06:10.066
And in this little three verses, he basically says, the reason a lot of us who do believe in the good news, we do believe in the gospel, are not able to handle our troubles is we do not know how to look.

06:10.818 --> 06:12.160
into the gospel.

06:12.300 --> 06:14.423
Let me start with this, and then I'll conclude with this.

06:15.124 --> 06:28.864
At the very end, it says, it was revealed to them that they were not serving themselves but you when they spoke of the things that have been told you by those who preached the gospel to you into which things even angels long to look.

06:29.725 --> 06:32.269
We referred to this last week, but now let me just show you what this means.

06:32.489 --> 06:36.715
When it says, into which things even angels long to look.

06:37.276 --> 06:38.898
First of all, the word long

06:39.970 --> 06:41.832
is an extremely strong word.

06:41.852 --> 06:46.136
It's a Greek word that means passion, it means obsession, and not Calvin Klein's.

06:47.897 --> 06:48.918
It means obsession.

06:51.261 --> 06:52.282
That's an amazing word.

06:53.663 --> 06:57.246
The word look usually means to gaze.

06:58.127 --> 07:03.832
So for example, in James chapter one, it talks about, there's an illustration used.

07:04.373 --> 07:09.938
It says, if a man sees, it beholds his face in a mirror.

07:10.274 --> 07:12.556
You know, now how do you behold your face in the mirror?

07:12.857 --> 07:15.159
You know, the word behold is a good English word.

07:15.239 --> 07:16.921
It's a better word even in this word gaze.

07:17.221 --> 07:19.924
The behold means you're not just look at it.

07:20.085 --> 07:20.785
Oh yeah, I saw her.

07:20.986 --> 07:21.526
I saw him.

07:22.127 --> 07:25.230
Behold means that it holds your gaze.

07:25.290 --> 07:30.396
It holds your attention or that you hold onto it and you look at it and you study it and you examine it, you see?

07:30.436 --> 07:35.681
And so what this is saying is the angels are obsessed with the gospel.

07:36.062 --> 07:37.223
Some people say, well, wait a minute.

07:37.263 --> 07:37.844
What does that mean?

07:37.984 --> 07:38.765
Angels want to look.

07:38.845 --> 07:39.986
It's a present tense.

07:40.866 --> 07:49.156
It's not saying, back then, when the prophets were speaking, the angels were intrigued because they wanted to know too, when was the Messiah coming?

07:49.316 --> 07:51.098
No, this is a present tense.

07:51.358 --> 07:56.445
And what it's saying is, the angels are obsessed with the gospel.

07:58.487 --> 08:00.329
They continually look into it.

08:00.710 --> 08:02.492
They long to look into it.

08:02.772 --> 08:04.434
They gaze into it.

08:06.594 --> 08:18.132
the way you'd look into a fire, a beautiful fire, the way you'd look at a beautiful person, the way you'd look into a kaleidoscope, look at the fireworks, you gaze at them, you can't get enough of them.

08:19.574 --> 08:28.007
They're obsessed with the gospel, they look into it all the time, and really what Peter's actually saying is, you better too, or else you will not be able to handle your troubles.

08:29.088 --> 08:30.370
And that's the reason why you can't.

08:31.131 --> 08:32.914
That's the gist of the passage.

08:33.186 --> 08:36.952
But having told you that just to the passage, he gives you a few how-tos in here.

08:37.633 --> 08:40.717
What does it mean to gaze into the gospel the way the angels do?

08:41.058 --> 08:41.578
Think about this.

08:41.599 --> 08:42.640
The angels are not idiots.

08:44.643 --> 08:46.446
The angels are pretty smart people.

08:47.347 --> 08:50.171
And therefore, here, let's get at this.

08:50.652 --> 08:52.555
Let's give the benefit of the doubt.

08:52.575 --> 08:56.340
They're probably smarter and overall more disciplined people than us.

08:58.143 --> 09:01.929
And therefore, the gospel cannot simply be a body of information.

09:01.969 --> 09:02.770
Isn't that right?

09:03.458 --> 09:06.122
I mean, you can only look into a body of information so long.

09:07.684 --> 09:11.790
So you get a book and you have to study it.

09:11.810 --> 09:12.692
You have to master it.

09:12.712 --> 09:15.276
So you read it and you master it and you master it and you master it.

09:15.296 --> 09:16.558
And let's say finally you memorize it.

09:16.578 --> 09:18.681
Well, at a certain point, you know it.

09:19.822 --> 09:32.882
And if the gospel was nothing but information, kind of a set of information, well, then the angels, you got to figure that their mental prowess and capacity is much greater than ours, they'd say, I know the gospel.

09:34.754 --> 09:37.120
Is there anybody out there that feels like they know the gospel?

09:37.862 --> 09:38.343
They know it.

09:38.965 --> 09:40.328
I want to talk about something else.

09:40.368 --> 09:41.411
I want to go beyond it.

09:41.852 --> 09:43.296
I want to talk about deeper teaching.

09:43.316 --> 09:52.018
One of the things, one of the giveaways of what a childish attitude that is, is if you ever watch children,

09:52.066 --> 09:54.329
You know, we baptize our children.

09:54.349 --> 09:55.410
We try to raise them in church.

09:55.431 --> 09:56.532
We try to teach them things.

09:56.913 --> 09:58.394
But it's so typical.

09:59.115 --> 10:08.828
If you try to teach a child a Bible story, if you try to, you know, you go into a sixth grade class, maybe some of you have tried this to teach Sunday school and so on, and you start to talk about the parable of the sower.

10:08.869 --> 10:11.973
You tell them about the, you know, this story or Jesus healing the blind man.

10:12.033 --> 10:15.878
And it's very typical if the kids have been in church for a while, they say, I already know that.

10:18.081 --> 10:19.182
I know Jesus died for my sins.

10:19.202 --> 10:20.464
What are you telling me about that for?

10:20.524 --> 10:21.906
Everybody knows that.

10:24.706 --> 10:26.228
But isn't it true of us?

10:27.409 --> 10:28.310
We think we know it.

10:29.212 --> 10:31.414
If you know it, why are you living the way you are?

10:31.434 --> 10:35.820
If you know it, why are your troubles overthrowing you?

10:35.860 --> 10:43.669
If you know it, why do you still, as we were saying earlier today, why do you still take your identity from what people say about you?

10:43.709 --> 10:46.273
Take your identity from what's happening, your accomplishments.

10:46.313 --> 10:48.075
Take your identity from your dress size.

10:48.135 --> 10:48.415
Why?

10:48.455 --> 10:53.842
If you really know the gospel.

10:54.530 --> 10:55.431
You don't know it.

10:55.831 --> 11:13.869
It's not just a sick, it is not just a body of information, but it's truly a kaleidoscope of insights, endless insights into how it applies to you, endless insights into the multi-dimensional richness of it, endless insights into what God has done.

11:14.069 --> 11:15.150
The angels are not dummies.

11:15.550 --> 11:23.698
If they are always obsessed with looking at it, this must be, or I should put it this way, do you know the bottomlessness of the gospel?

11:24.482 --> 11:24.943
They do.

11:24.983 --> 11:29.770
Now, if you want to learn how to gaze in the gospel, let's just take a look at this.

11:29.790 --> 11:32.594
There's really, in a sense, three things that it teaches us.

11:34.137 --> 11:37.201
First of all, you better understand what the gospel is.

11:37.242 --> 11:41.268
Inside the Bible, what is the gospel?

11:41.789 --> 11:42.770
Notice it says,

11:42.978 --> 11:46.202
Well, let me just kind of give you an overview here.

11:46.242 --> 12:00.058
Concerning the salvation, the prophets who spoke of the grace that was to come to you, searched intently and with the greatest care, trying to find out the time and the circumstances to which the Spirit of Christ in them was pointing when he predicted the sufferings of Christ and the glories that would follow.

12:00.518 --> 12:04.543
This is telling us that the Old Testament prophets knew about Christ coming.

12:04.603 --> 12:06.665
They knew that someone would come to save us.

12:07.927 --> 12:09.028
God's pardon me.

12:09.969 --> 12:10.770
Jesus said,

12:11.202 --> 12:13.526
Abraham rejoiced to see my day.

12:14.969 --> 12:18.635
Christ was saying that Abraham knew I was coming but had no idea about when or where.

12:19.376 --> 12:22.181
And the important word here is the circumstances.

12:22.962 --> 12:26.869
The first thing, and I'll try to be brief because we've mentioned this before, but it's very, very important.

12:27.691 --> 12:32.619
The gospel is a report of a historic event.

12:33.340 --> 12:36.626
The gospel is not simply wise sayings.

12:37.090 --> 12:40.735
The gospel, if you're going to gaze into the gospel, you have to realize where it is and what it is.

12:41.496 --> 12:43.639
The gospel is not just simply why sayings.

12:44.560 --> 12:46.683
It's not just simply depictions of virtue.

12:47.284 --> 12:51.089
You know, the myths of the Greeks and the Romans depicted virtue.

12:51.470 --> 12:56.917
Here's Hercules and he tells us something about virtue and we listen to the story and we say, ah, that's how we should all be.

12:57.178 --> 12:58.019
Is that the gospel?

12:58.319 --> 12:59.060
Absolutely not.

13:00.102 --> 13:04.007
In fact, it says that the prophets knew that there would be circumstances.

13:04.027 --> 13:05.970
There would be a historical moment

13:06.626 --> 13:08.670
in which this great salvation happened.

13:09.672 --> 13:24.198
And later on, it actually says here in verse 12, it says, when the things that the prophets spoke about are predicted, the apostles spoke of those things that have now been told you by those who preached the gospel.

13:24.218 --> 13:27.384
And the word told there in the old King James Bible is the word report.

13:28.245 --> 13:29.568
The gospel is a report.

13:29.628 --> 13:30.770
What's a reporter do?

13:31.266 --> 13:36.671
Well, some reporters do philosophize and some reporters do interpret, but the main job of reporters to tell you what happened.

13:38.173 --> 13:40.375
And the essence of the gospel is it's not a teaching.

13:40.495 --> 13:41.696
It's not a lot of wise sayings.

13:41.756 --> 13:42.517
It's not ethical.

13:43.238 --> 13:44.078
You know how to live.

13:45.079 --> 13:47.722
Oh, the gospel leads to ethics.

13:48.322 --> 13:49.724
The gospel leads to wisdom.

13:50.144 --> 13:54.589
The gospel leads to wise teachings, but the gospel primarily is a report of an event.

13:54.669 --> 13:55.650
Let me explain.

13:55.710 --> 14:00.274
You know, the word gospel comes from the word that meant good news.

14:00.706 --> 14:04.730
which means the heralds would come into town and say, good news, something has happened.

14:05.090 --> 14:12.398
Heralds did not come into town and say, good news, a penny saved is a penny earned.

14:13.159 --> 14:17.683
The herald did not rock in and say, good news, crime does not pay.

14:17.743 --> 14:20.826
The herald did not come in with wise things.

14:21.447 --> 14:28.434
The herald came in and says, something has happened in history that changes everything and you must respond to it.

14:30.402 --> 14:36.151
The herald might come in and say, the crime does not pay because the king has triumph, because he's landed.

14:36.471 --> 14:42.741
But the difference is the wise things are based on the gospel, on a fact, on a report.

14:44.824 --> 14:47.728
Why is there so much pain and suffering in the world?

14:48.189 --> 14:54.258
And how do we handle it in a way that won't destroy us, but could actually make us stronger, wiser, and more hopeful?

14:54.658 --> 15:04.242
All month long on Gospel and Life, Tim Keller is teaching from the book of 1 Peter, and looking at how Peter encouraged early believers who were facing intense suffering in pain.

15:04.282 --> 15:07.570
In his book, Walking with God Through Pain and Suffering,

15:07.618 --> 15:15.465
Dr. Keller takes a deeper look at how, with God's help, we can face life's most intense challenges and confront the hard questions on suffering.

15:16.025 --> 15:22.271
Through deep pastoral insight and real life stories, Dr. Keller explores how we can face pain and suffering in our own lives.

15:22.811 --> 15:32.319
This month, walking with God through pain and suffering is our thank you for your gift to help Gospel and Life share the message of Christ's love and compassion with people all over the world.

15:32.840 --> 15:37.604
So request your copy today at gospelandlife.com.

15:37.584 --> 15:42.391
Now, here's Dr. Keller with the remainder of today's teaching.

15:45.495 --> 16:01.298
Now, if you happen to believe that gazing at the gospel means looking at all, looking to sermon on the mounts and looking at the way we're supposed to live and love thy neighbor as thyself, if you're the kind of person who says, I want to be a Christian, I want to experience all these great things, but I don't know whether I believe that Jesus was God.

16:01.826 --> 16:04.809
I don't know whether I believe that He died on a cross for my sins.

16:04.849 --> 16:06.952
I don't know whether I believe the accounts of the gospel.

16:06.972 --> 16:07.913
I'm not sure about that.

16:09.955 --> 16:17.003
But all that matters to me is that Jesus is a wonderful model of compassionate living, and I want to follow that model.

16:22.789 --> 16:27.234
You think that Jesus Christ's model is good news?

16:27.354 --> 16:30.578
My friends, Jesus Christ is so wonderful.

16:30.850 --> 16:35.875
His example is so great, his wisdom is so wonderful that he damns us with every word.

16:37.156 --> 16:38.458
He's nothing but depressing.

16:39.619 --> 16:51.090
If he didn't come to die for your sins and to do something in history, if he's simply a model, if he just comes with wise sayings, live like this, obey the golden rule, if that's the good news, we're lost, we're lost.

16:51.570 --> 16:54.093
Think about it, there's nothing encouraging about Jesus Christ.

16:54.373 --> 16:59.218
If he comes as a teacher, if he comes as a wise person, if he comes as a philosopher, no.

17:01.026 --> 17:04.250
You don't have to believe that Jesus is God coming to flesh.

17:05.812 --> 17:11.179
You don't have to believe that He died on the cross for our sins, to change us forever.

17:13.322 --> 17:20.271
You don't have to believe that He rose physically from the grave, and now stands at the right hand of the Father, and He represents us before the Father.

17:20.291 --> 17:26.839
You don't have to believe that, but if you want philosophy instead of that, go to other religions.

17:26.899 --> 17:28.882
They're all about that, don't you see?

17:29.378 --> 17:33.004
If you just want to teach her, if you just want an example, go to them because that's what they're about.

17:33.064 --> 17:34.987
But Christianity never has been about that.

17:36.009 --> 17:37.932
The gospel is he has done something for you.

17:38.233 --> 17:39.395
Your sins are forgiven.

17:39.435 --> 17:42.099
Death has been broken.

17:42.139 --> 17:44.984
He died in your place and he rose triumphant over the grave.

17:45.224 --> 17:45.966
That's the gospel.

17:46.847 --> 17:47.208
Oh, listen.

17:47.949 --> 17:50.012
The Bible is full of how to win over worry.

17:51.014 --> 17:53.458
It helps you how to deal with guilt feelings.

17:53.570 --> 17:54.972
How to raise a happy family?

17:55.733 --> 17:56.695
How to overcome bitterness?

17:56.735 --> 17:57.576
How to phrase grief?

17:57.816 --> 17:59.839
Of course, but only because there's a gospel.

17:59.899 --> 18:09.273
Otherwise, everything, all the other things that the Bible says, everything else about the Bible is Babel.

18:10.295 --> 18:11.096
It's nonsense.

18:12.378 --> 18:13.539
There's no help for your worry.

18:13.559 --> 18:16.524
There's no way to deal with grief unless these things actually happened.

18:17.085 --> 18:17.565
Don't you see?

18:19.208 --> 18:20.850
And that's very, very important to realize.

18:21.986 --> 18:31.421
All the great things you see in the Bible, the philosophies, all the wisdom, all that stuff, all the how to handle worry and how to deal with grief and how to over don't you dare think that that is the gospel.

18:31.461 --> 18:32.823
That's a consequence of the gospel.

18:32.863 --> 18:41.377
The gospel is that Jesus Christ at a certain moment in circumstances of time suffered, died for us.

18:43.100 --> 18:43.761
That's the first thing.

18:44.261 --> 18:44.923
That's the gospel.

18:44.963 --> 18:45.844
That's what you have to look at.

18:45.904 --> 18:49.650
What He's done for you, if you just gaze, if you think

18:49.890 --> 18:56.744
What it means to gaze into the gospel and be obsessed with the gospel is just to look at what he says, turn the other cheek.

19:00.812 --> 19:01.474
Be generous.

19:02.135 --> 19:04.921
Give and don't let your right hand know what your left hand is doing.

19:08.268 --> 19:10.312
Forgive everybody, seventy times seven.

19:10.392 --> 19:11.314
Read all that stuff.

19:11.394 --> 19:17.821
If you think that's what it means to gaze into the gospel, all that stuff is wonderful to read if you first understand that he's actually done something.

19:18.241 --> 19:20.003
What you're gazing into is what he's done for you.

19:20.484 --> 19:26.370
Secondly, the second thing you have to do is the way to gaze into the gospel is read the Bible.

19:26.530 --> 19:29.273
Now maybe that's pretty obvious, but I guess we better lay it out here.

19:30.214 --> 19:37.202
Peter is saying that the place you find this wonderful gospel that the angels are obsessed with

19:37.666 --> 19:41.812
is to read the prophets of the Old Testament and the apostles of the New Testament.

19:41.832 --> 19:46.419
See in verse 10 it says, the prophets foretold it in a kind of shadowy way.

19:47.541 --> 19:55.413
And they yearned to see when it was going to happen, but they never really able to tell all the details.

19:55.493 --> 20:00.521
However, the same spirit that told the prophets that Jesus was coming.

20:01.082 --> 20:06.290
Now it says in verse 12, it guides the apostles who preach the gospel to you.

20:06.850 --> 20:08.092
Now here's what this teaches us.

20:08.392 --> 20:10.515
Secondly, you have to read the Bible.

20:11.616 --> 20:12.938
You have to gaze into the Bible.

20:14.460 --> 20:18.746
One of the things that's wonderful here is this is telling us, this is giving us a doctrine of the Scripture.

20:18.766 --> 20:19.347
You know what it is?

20:19.967 --> 20:27.858
The doctrine of the Scripture is that the things that the prophets and the apostles said are actually the words of the Spirit of God.

20:28.834 --> 20:32.117
you have a wonderful doctrine of the scripture, and I can only mention it very briefly.

20:32.638 --> 20:37.543
On the one hand, you've got a kind of stenographer approach to the inspiration of the scripture.

20:37.583 --> 20:50.916
Many people seem to think that God just sort of sent in some kind of, they zapped, you might say, the prophets and the apostles, and the prophets and the apostles in a kind of stenographic way, just sort of wrote things down.

20:51.697 --> 20:56.402
When actually you see here that they were involved

20:57.218 --> 20:59.542
They searched out.

20:59.742 --> 21:00.463
They were looking.

21:01.244 --> 21:08.515
They said, gosh, look, God's showing us something that the Messiah is going to come, but they searched intently to know when it was going to come.

21:08.535 --> 21:10.598
Do you see what an interesting statement this is?

21:11.259 --> 21:13.282
It means that they were human beings.

21:13.803 --> 21:15.466
They didn't lose their cognition.

21:15.506 --> 21:16.628
They didn't lose control.

21:17.148 --> 21:22.396
And yet, what was coming to them, they knew, was not a product of their own wisdom.

21:24.520 --> 21:26.162
Their words were God's words.

21:26.434 --> 21:36.004
If you want a perfect example of this, in Acts chapter 425, Peter says, the Lord God who by the mouth of David did say by the Holy Spirit.

21:37.005 --> 21:38.005
And then he quotes Psalm 2.

21:38.786 --> 21:48.456
Listen, the Lord God who by the mouth of David did say by the Holy Spirit, that's how they understand, that's how the biblical writers understand what else is happening in the Bible.

21:48.916 --> 21:54.642
They know that David wrote Psalm 2, but they know that the Holy Spirit so moved David

21:55.138 --> 22:01.167
that whatever David says, God says, and that's how you have to read the Bible.

22:01.808 --> 22:03.050
You have to look at it that way.

22:03.210 --> 22:07.737
Oh, somebody says, well, how can you have that kind of view of the Bible?

22:08.558 --> 22:10.080
How can you have a view of its authority?

22:10.221 --> 22:11.743
There's really only two ways to read the Bible.

22:12.264 --> 22:17.171
You can either accept what Jesus said about it, because this was Jesus' view too, and I don't have time to go into it.

22:17.812 --> 22:24.562
You can accept what Peter and Jesus and all those folks said about it, and you can let the Bible have authority over your thinking or

22:25.378 --> 22:33.751
you can decide that you're the authority, and you know best how to go through it and sort out what's right and wrong, and you can let yourself be the authority over what the Bible says.

22:33.791 --> 22:39.860
You can either let your own reason be ascendant over the Bible, or you can let the Bible be ascendant over your own reason.

22:40.401 --> 22:51.538
Those are the only two possibilities, and as a result, if you are unwilling, if you're unwilling to take

22:51.682 --> 22:54.825
this view of the Scripture, it's very hard to gaze into the gospel.

22:55.245 --> 22:58.889
I'm not saying that in order to be a Christian, you have to believe every word of the Bible.

23:00.510 --> 23:04.194
I'm saying that if you want to be a consistent Christian, you do.

23:04.854 --> 23:10.740
Because it's really silly to say, I believe what Jesus says, I believe he died for me, he's my Lord, but I don't believe what he taught about the Scripture.

23:11.661 --> 23:14.363
What Peter says is the same thing that Jesus said.

23:14.403 --> 23:15.584
Peter was Jesus' apostle.

23:16.325 --> 23:19.268
He looks at the Scripture and says, it's the work of the Spirit of God.

23:19.929 --> 23:21.490
You've got to trust the Bible.

23:21.954 --> 23:27.743
or else you'll never be able to see it as what it is, a letter from God to you about the gospel.

23:28.604 --> 23:36.997
Last of all, it says the only way you're going to ever find the Bible making sense to you is if you see it's all about the sufferings and glory of Christ.

23:38.158 --> 23:40.342
Everything is about the sufferings and glory of Christ.

23:41.243 --> 23:46.110
According to Peter, all of the Old Testament is about the sufferings and glory of Christ.

23:46.611 --> 23:48.113
Well, somebody says, that's not right.

23:48.434 --> 23:49.615
Well, sure, look at the prophecies.

23:49.655 --> 23:51.378
The prophecies are all about Christ.

23:51.682 --> 23:54.507
We're told in Genesis 3 that the Redeemer will be human.

23:55.328 --> 23:57.692
We're told in Isaiah 9, you know, he's a mighty God.

23:57.732 --> 24:00.737
He's a manual in Isaiah 7 that he'll be God.

24:01.418 --> 24:04.843
We're told that he'll suffer and be killed like in Isaiah 53.

24:05.444 --> 24:08.048
We're told that he'll rise again Psalm 16.

24:08.088 --> 24:10.052
You will not let your Holy One seek corruption.

24:10.612 --> 24:13.758
And so you go through and you see the prophecies are about Jesus.

24:13.818 --> 24:16.562
Well, somebody says, well, what about Leviticus?

24:18.178 --> 24:23.486
What about all that stuff that's so hard to read about the sacrifices, about the tabernacle and all that?

24:23.506 --> 24:24.447
That's all about Jesus.

24:24.888 --> 24:28.453
Jesus was the sacrifice that the Old Testament was pointing to.

24:28.513 --> 24:30.716
Jesus was the bread on the altar.

24:31.177 --> 24:32.999
Jesus was the lampstand in the holy place.

24:33.039 --> 24:35.603
Jesus was the temple itself.

24:35.623 --> 24:37.005
He's the place where you meet God.

24:37.506 --> 24:39.368
Well, somebody says, what about the law?

24:40.310 --> 24:40.871
Oh, look it.

24:41.351 --> 24:43.314
The law is all about Jesus.

24:43.682 --> 24:50.150
When you read the Ten Commandments, when you read the Proverbs, when you read any part of the Old Testament, you know what you're looking at?

24:51.091 --> 24:53.854
Yes, somebody says, sure, it's about what I'm supposed to do.

24:53.874 --> 25:05.688
Not first of all, if you learn how to read the Bible through the sufferings and glory of Christ, you will see that first of all, the law is telling you about the moral excellence of Jesus and what He has done for you.

25:06.649 --> 25:07.410
Read that stuff.

25:08.251 --> 25:09.192
He did this for me.

25:09.652 --> 25:10.994
He fulfilled this for me.

25:11.234 --> 25:13.778
all of the moral perfection of Jesus.

25:13.818 --> 25:17.064
Because he's the only one who ever loved the Lord is God with all his heart, soul, strength in mind.

25:17.084 --> 25:19.668
He's the only one that ever loved his neighbor as himself perfectly.

25:19.969 --> 25:25.619
He fulfilled the law and the law is all about the righteousness that has been imputed to you when you receive him as Savior.

25:26.600 --> 25:27.662
Do you read the law like that?

25:28.904 --> 25:30.908
History makes you feel good if you do it that way.

25:31.729 --> 25:32.430
Oh, that's not all.

25:33.492 --> 25:34.093
One last thing.

25:35.556 --> 25:36.978
Even the history of Israel

25:37.410 --> 25:39.654
is all about the sufferings and glory of Jesus.

25:39.734 --> 25:41.077
Jesus was the true prophet.

25:41.718 --> 25:42.880
Jesus was the true priest.

25:43.842 --> 25:44.944
Jesus was the true king.

25:45.345 --> 25:48.370
And so all the history of all the other prophets, priests, and kings just point to Jesus.

25:48.390 --> 25:50.334
But more than that, you know what Israel was?

25:50.995 --> 25:58.650
God, out of all the nations of the earth, shows one nation and says, I want you to be faithful to me and keep my commandments.

25:59.491 --> 26:01.074
But a lot of them didn't.

26:01.922 --> 26:07.671
And so out of, you remember the ten tribes, they eventually were pushed away and they were punished and they were lost.

26:08.011 --> 26:09.554
So then you're down to one tribe, Judah.

26:10.435 --> 26:14.782
Well, you keep the covenant, but a lot of them didn't, and they were sent away in exile.

26:14.842 --> 26:17.526
So only a remnant came back after the exile to Babylon.

26:17.887 --> 26:18.608
Will you do it?

26:19.069 --> 26:20.651
Down, down, down.

26:21.432 --> 26:25.358
In the end, how big is Israel, according to the New Testament?

26:25.478 --> 26:26.260
How big is Israel?

26:27.021 --> 26:28.904
How many people have been faithful to the covenant?

26:28.964 --> 26:30.386
How many people have been faithful?

26:30.626 --> 26:32.088
How small is the remnant?

26:32.388 --> 26:33.729
I'll tell you who Israel is.

26:33.770 --> 26:35.011
There's only one person left.

26:35.752 --> 26:38.655
According to the Bible, one person left.

26:39.356 --> 26:55.474
You know, in the book of Hosea, it talks about the fact that when the Israelites were called out of Egypt, when God led them out under Moses, and Hosea says out of Egypt, I called my son, and yet in the Gospel of Matthew,

26:57.090 --> 27:02.257
Matthew is able to apply that to Jesus himself because Jesus is the true Israel.

27:02.317 --> 27:04.680
He's the only one that fulfilled the covenant.

27:04.740 --> 27:11.870
And that means that all of the blessings promised to the children of Abraham belong to Jesus alone.

27:12.190 --> 27:13.792
He alone inherits the promises.

27:13.852 --> 27:15.114
He alone inherits the blessings.

27:15.154 --> 27:16.135
He is the true Israel.

27:16.356 --> 27:18.098
All of the history of Israel was about him.

27:18.402 --> 27:20.124
All the ceremonial laws about Him.

27:20.164 --> 27:23.208
All of the law and the wisdom is about Him.

27:23.248 --> 27:25.010
All of the prophecy is about Him.

27:25.070 --> 27:27.133
All the ceremonial, it's all about Him.

27:27.473 --> 27:28.655
Do you know how to read the Bible?

27:30.196 --> 27:32.379
That it's all about the sufferings and glory of Jesus.

27:34.442 --> 27:39.107
If you don't, the Bible is going to be to you like it was to Mark Twain.

27:39.127 --> 27:42.632
Mark Twain used to have nightmares at night about the Bible.

27:42.692 --> 27:47.858
He used to dream about this huge Bible put on his chest, crushing him.

27:48.194 --> 27:49.896
breaking his bones, suffocating him.

27:49.936 --> 27:50.917
He couldn't breathe.

27:51.698 --> 28:00.446
If you read the law, except as the sufferings about the sufferings and glory of Christ, if you read the ceremony, if you read the history of Israel, it'll crush you.

28:00.506 --> 28:04.891
That's not how you gaze at the gospel.

28:05.291 --> 28:09.495
You have to read everything as if it's about the sufferings and glory of Jesus.

28:10.757 --> 28:11.798
Let me conclude this way.

28:12.659 --> 28:16.082
Until you learn how to read the whole Bible through the gospel,

28:16.482 --> 28:21.047
so that you see actually the gospel is enshrined in the Bible in a thousand different ways.

28:21.087 --> 28:22.929
So it's like a glorious kaleidoscope.

28:22.949 --> 28:31.359
There's never ending different number of ways in which the gospel is laid out there for you so that you get it, you get the richness of it, you get it over and over again.

28:31.419 --> 28:35.003
So it permeates you and saturates you and changes the way you do everything.

28:35.824 --> 28:40.008
But it only happens if you read everything in the Old Ann New Testament through this one.

28:40.429 --> 28:42.311
It's all about the sufferings and glory of Christ.

28:42.912 --> 28:44.914
In Luke 24,

28:46.050 --> 28:51.876
On the road to Emmaus, Jesus, after his resurrection, meets these two downcast disciples.

28:53.398 --> 28:54.839
And of course, they don't recognize Jesus.

28:56.101 --> 28:57.202
And he says, what's the problem?

28:58.383 --> 28:59.745
And they say to him, get this.

29:00.806 --> 29:06.232
Basically, they say, you know, we thought that Jesus Christ would redeem Israel.

29:06.572 --> 29:09.115
We thought he would redeem us, and yet he died on a cross.

29:12.579 --> 29:15.762
We thought he'd redeem us, but instead, he died on a cross.

29:17.538 --> 29:24.025
Jesus looked at them and he said, oh, foolish and slow of heart to believe all that the prophets have spoken.

29:24.085 --> 29:33.355
And then, beginning with Moses and all the prophets, he explained to them what was said in all scripture concerning himself.

29:37.619 --> 29:43.826
And he said, did not the Christ have to suffer these things and then enter into his glory.

29:44.290 --> 29:52.542
You see, what Jesus said was, if you don't understand what's going on in life, it's because you haven't learned to see everything through the sufferings and glory of the Messiah.

29:52.562 --> 29:58.071
He proves that every part of the Scripture, every part of the Scripture, is about his sufferings and his glory.

29:58.531 --> 30:00.434
Have you learned to read the Scripture that way?

30:01.255 --> 30:04.360
There's some people out here who don't believe the Scripture's a coherent body.

30:04.500 --> 30:05.321
I challenge you.

30:05.421 --> 30:06.062
I charge you.

30:06.183 --> 30:13.874
I dare you to start reading the Bible carefully, to start reading the Bible systematically and comprehensively and say, is it all about Jesus?

30:14.914 --> 30:20.640
If you begin to read the Bible like that, I'm sorry, you'll never gaze into the gospel simply by reading John 3 16 every morning.

30:21.601 --> 30:32.994
You'll never gaze into the gospel and get obsessed with the gospel and have your life changed by the gospel unless you start to actually look into the words of the prophets and the apostles, read the Scripture all through the suffering and glory of Christ.

30:34.436 --> 30:36.438
Do you understand the bottomlessness of the gospel?

30:38.120 --> 30:41.664
Oh, he can make your joys to weep and your griefs to sing.

30:41.704 --> 30:43.826
The hymn writer says.

30:45.314 --> 30:48.137
And your own sufferings, you'll begin to see why they are there.

30:48.377 --> 30:51.020
You won't be confused like the people on the road to Emmaus.

30:52.221 --> 30:55.864
We thought he was going to redeem us, but instead he died on the cross.

30:56.885 --> 30:58.787
Oh, foolish of heart, don't be like them.

31:00.088 --> 31:00.769
Don't be like them.

31:00.809 --> 31:02.471
Gaze into the gospel, let's pray.

31:02.931 --> 31:14.162
Our Father, we ask that you'd now help us to be disciplined enough to read the Scripture, to be smart enough to

31:15.618 --> 31:27.135
to trust the scripture, to trust it, to be obedient enough to come to it and seek to read it through the sufferings and glory of your son.

31:27.997 --> 31:34.687
We ask that you'd help us to look into it just the way the angels do until we become as full of Christ as they are.

31:34.987 --> 31:37.010
In Jesus' name we pray, amen.

31:42.850 --> 31:46.717
Thanks for listening to today's teaching from Tim Keller here at Gospel and Life.

31:47.318 --> 31:53.348
For the 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday, Gospel and Life would like to email you a daily lint devotional.

31:53.749 --> 31:57.535
You can sign up to receive these daily emails at gospelandlife.com.

31:58.136 --> 31:59.939
That's gospelandlife.com.

